WALT KUHN
66 WEST ELEVENTH STREET
NEW YORK 
Nov. 24/26
Dear Miss Roullier.,
Thanks for your letter o/November nineteenth. I have just seen the chardin exhibition.  It is a beauty. That man certainly knew how to caress with paint--
as regards my show for Chicago would it not be possible to have it a bit earlier? Say opening about March first?
You see my New York show will close about February tenth, and to wait until March 15th would make a very bad lapse--Besides early in March, I expect to be in a position to get off for a week or two, to come on with the show, this might not be possible at a later date. Will you think it over

WALT KUHN
56 WEST ELEVENTH STREET
NEW YORK  Mar 26/27
Dear Alice.,
I don't have to tell you how pleased I am with the way you steered the ship for me in Chicago To say that everything was bang-up and complete would be putting it mildly. -- I am yours forever!! My Litho show is going strong here--artists especially are enthusiastic. I shall send on thelacking? prints for your show. 
Many thanks for the catalogs, they will be very useful-
Be sure to arrange for at least a few minutes talk on your way to the boat. Certain things which were vague to me before, have cleared since my return from Chicago--they will keep, but you must know about them before you sail, as I believe they have a direct bearing on art-matters in Chicago - for which you are ginning up so much unselfish energy--Let me know the name of your boat as soon as you book passage. 
In the meantime as ever
Faithfully
Walt Kuhn

WALT KUHN
66 WEST ELEVENTH STREET
NEW YORK 
May 8/27
Dear Alice
Thanks for your note. Judging from all the controversy caused by my modest endeavors at the Institute, you are in for like "indignations"? with the lithographs. I hope you had just half the fun I did, reading the profound remarks of the art critics of your Town--
At present I am working on some things for "Merry go round" The successor to "Americana"--The show is booked to open at the Klaw Theatre on Decoration day--It's lots of fun, and just the sort

THE UNIVERSITY OF KANSAS
SCHOOL OF FINE ARTS
LAWRENCE
14 March 1927
DEPARTMENT OF DRAWING AND PAINTING
Miss Alice Roullier
The Arts Club of Chicago
My Dear Miss Roullier--
I understand that the small picture: Blind Beggar (No. 18 on my list) has been sold in the Kansas City Exhibition. So if it is not included in the shipment, that will be the reason for its absence.-- -- Also the Hamlet Composition (No. 23) has been withdrawn. -- -- The pictures should leave Kansas City (according & promise) either this Thursday evening or tomorrow Tuesday morning, which should bring them to Chicago in ample time to go on the walls. -- -- Unfortunately, I have no available photographs of my work; they are all kept filed in scrap-books, and cannot be spared. I should be glad if you can have press-cuttings and
